Let $\omega = r(\cos \theta + i\sin \theta) = re^{i\theta}$, where $r$ and $\theta$ are real numbers with $r > 0$. Then by the definition
\[\omega = \frac{\omega^2 + 1}{\omega + 1} = \frac{(r^2\cos 2\theta + 1)\left(\cos(\pi/2 - i\log(r) + 2\theta)\right) + i\sin(\pi/2 - i\log(r) + 2\theta)}{\cos(\pi/2 - i\log(r) + \theta) + i\sin(\pi/2 - i\log(r) + \theta)}.\]Multiplying both sides by $(\cos(\pi/2 - i\log(r) + 2\theta) + i\sin(\pi/2 - i\log(r) + 2\theta))$ and equating the imaginary parts, we obtain\[r^2\cos 2\theta + 1 = \cos(\pi/2 - i\log(r) + 2\theta).\]Taking the absolute value of both sides and using the identity $|\cos x + i\sin x| = 1$, we obtain\[r^2 = |\cos(\pi/2 - i\log(r) + 2\theta) + i\sin(\pi/2 - i\log(r) + 2\theta)| = 1,\]which implies $r = 1$. In addition, applying the inverse tangent function to both sides of $r^2\cos 2\theta + 1 = \cos(\pi/2 - i\log(r) + 2\theta)$ and noting that $\arctan$ takes on all real values, we get \[\theta = \frac{n\pi}{2n},n \ge 1,\]which is the solution set. Thus, our solution set is \[\boxed{1, -1}.\]

